Right-sizing and idle elimination.

The first lever on every cost review is resources that aren't doing the work they're sized for, and there are two patterns. Over-sized: an m-five-dot-four-x-large running at eight percent C-P-U for the last ninety days; drop it to an m-five-dot-large, or move to a Graviton-based equivalent, and save sixty percent or more. And idle: an E-C-2 instance that gets no requests but was forgotten after a project ended, a dev R-D-S that runs twenty-four-seven but is only used during office hours, an E-B-S volume detached from any instance for months, or an Elastic I-P that nobody is using, which is billed precisely when it's unattached.

Two A-W-S tools find these. Compute Optimizer is A-W-S's right-sizing engine; it analyses fourteen days of CloudWatch data for E-C-2, Auto Scaling Groups, E-B-S volumes, Lambda, E-C-S, and R-D-S, and recommends a specific smaller or differently-shaped resource, like switch this instance to m-six-g-dot-large for a projected monthly saving, and it accounts for performance impact. Trusted Advisor flags idle resources in its Cost Optimization category, idle load balancers, underutilised E-B-S volumes, and low-utilisation E-C-2 instances, though the full set of checks needs Business or Enterprise Support.

Beyond right-sizing, two structural levers. Schedule non-production: stop dev and test instances nights and weekends, and roughly seventy percent of a twenty-four-seven bill vanishes for office-hours workloads. And storage lifecycle: S3 Intelligent-Tiering and lifecycle rules move cold data to cheaper classes automatically, and you delete unattached E-B-S volumes and old snapshots. The mindset is simple: the cheapest resource is the one you turned off.
